    anymore. What's your name, young man?"
  BJORN: [a rusty grin -- 'young man' lands, given the dragon-years] "Bjorn. And
    you're too kind by half, ma'am. My pleasure."
  GRELOD: "Bjorn. You'll make some lucky woman very happy one day." [a warm laugh;
    she pats his arm and moves on toward the orphanage with her basket.]
  BJORN: [to himself, pleased, a little flustered] "...Huh. Riften's not all bad."
  The horror is RETROACTIVE. Hold this beat. It pays off the instant he learns who
  she was -- see BJORN, DOUBTING below.

BJORN, DOUBTING (the hinge -- after he learns THAT was her):
  When Bjorn realizes the gracious woman he just charmed is the "child-breaking
  monster" the party described, he can't square it. He goes quiet, then:
  "...That sweet old woman? The one with the blankets? You're SURE about this?
  The whole city loves her. I just -- maybe your information's wrong." Their own
  moral anchor -- the man who'll kill for a child -- doubts THEM. His own charmed
  reaction makes him want to disbelieve it. This is the loudest possible proof
  that no one will ever believe Orion, and it isolates him: he can't even lean on
  the party. (If pressed with hard evidence he'll come around -- reluctantly, sick
  about it -- but the instinctive doubt is the point.)

